WEBVTT

00:08.720 --> 00:12.640
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

00:28.280 --> 00:33.580
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

00:36.180 --> 00:37.900
And here are your hosts.

00:42.060 --> 00:51.620
This is Bill Vernon and Daryl Lane. In 1982, Science Fiction lost one of its most brilliant, innovative and original writers, Phillip K. Dick, dead at 53 of a stroke.

00:52.400 --> 00:57.980
Dick left us just as he was finally being discovered by a large number of readers, both science fiction fans and non-fans.

00:57.980 --> 01:08.480
Dick had struggled since the early 1950s to write science fiction, full-time, and he produced an immense number of novels and stories, including the 1963 Hugo Wynning novel, The Man in the High Castle.

01:09.000 --> 01:12.820
However, for a long time, his fans were a relatively small number of loyal followers.

01:13.320 --> 01:22.380
Right. For years, Dick's writing just never really caught on with the majority of science fiction fans. This was especially true in the 50s and early 60s, when fans were more interested in hardware science fiction.

01:22.380 --> 01:28.160
Well, with the social changes of the late 60s and the advent of the new wave, Dick's writing achieved a more deserving status.

01:28.760 --> 01:35.080
We talked with a friend of Dick's, Paul Williams, who was known in science fiction for his perceptive portrait of Dick in an article in Rolling Stone.

01:35.220 --> 01:39.080
Others will remember Williams as a rock journalist and as the founder of Craw Daddy magazine.

01:39.700 --> 01:44.440
Williams met Dick at the 1968 World Science Fiction Convention in Oakland. They became friends immediately.

01:44.880 --> 01:47.560
Williams graciously consented to talking about Dick with us.

01:47.560 --> 01:54.260
During most of his writing career, Dick made very little money. We asked Williams why Dick stuck to writing in the face of poor economic returns.

01:54.800 --> 02:11.500
I think a real commitment, first of all, to the ultimate, I don't know if I want to say seriousness, but that's really a real commitment to what he was creating and what he wanted to say.

02:11.500 --> 02:16.420
I think it's a great story that always, when he's written, it's been because he had to write.

02:16.840 --> 02:21.920
And it was equally true that it became the only way he could make a living.

02:22.240 --> 02:30.560
It's a classic freelance writer situation where even though you're okay if you only get $1,500 for a science fiction novel,

02:31.320 --> 02:39.540
then what you have to do to stay alive is write six of them in a year, which he came pretty close to doing at one point.

02:56.020 --> 03:00.400
But Dick didn't stick strictly to writing science fiction. He wrote mainstream novels as well.

03:00.400 --> 03:10.400
It was not until early in the 1960s that he gave up trying to become a successful mainstream writer.

03:11.240 --> 03:17.320
And even then, he didn't give up. Although it felt like that to him at the time.

03:17.480 --> 03:22.860
He just put it away in the back burner, having tried very, very hard for 10 years.

03:23.440 --> 03:27.840
The first 10 years, which while he had his first 10 or so science fiction novel published,

03:27.840 --> 03:31.100
he wrote a mainstream novel for every science fiction novelist.

03:32.600 --> 03:40.220
So really, he was writing two novels for $1,000 advance, one of which would be published in an A-Double novel

03:40.220 --> 03:44.340
and the other of which would go from publisher to publisher and just be turned down.

03:46.300 --> 03:48.940
And there is still 10 or 11 of those in a published novel.

03:49.600 --> 03:53.120
So there are in existence several manuscripts of mainstream novels written by Dick.

03:53.520 --> 03:56.040
We asked Williams if there is any chance these will ever be published.

03:56.040 --> 04:08.160
I think that it's inevitable. Bill had mixed opinions about their quality and I haven't read most of them.

04:10.600 --> 04:18.840
But it seems clear, although we may be surprised, that there's nothing as polished or as good as Confessions of the Craft Artists,

04:18.920 --> 04:22.220
which I think is actually one of his five or six best books.

04:24.620 --> 04:29.180
But because of the interest in those works, it seems inevitable at this point.

04:29.480 --> 04:35.960
So one way or another, they will most or probably all be published within the next 10 or 20 years.

04:38.140 --> 04:45.960
But probably still by small publishers, not by New York publishers.

04:46.740 --> 04:49.680
More about Philip K. Dick with Paul Williams on our next show.

04:56.640 --> 04:59.160
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show,

04:59.440 --> 05:02.080
a production of the Permian Basin Science Fiction Association

05:02.080 --> 05:05.240
produced in conjunction with Odessa College in Odessa, Texas.

