06:30.320 --> 06:31.100
This is Philip K. Dick,

06:31.100 --> 06:36.960
The late Philip K. Dick published some 35 science fiction novels and a few mainstream ones as well.

06:37.200 --> 06:41.540
Among Dick's well-known science fiction novels are the Hugo Award-winning The Man in the High Castle,

06:42.040 --> 06:45.160
Martian Time Slip, The Three-Stigmata of Palmer Eldridge,

06:45.500 --> 06:47.800
The Androids' Dream of Electric Sheep, and Ubic.

06:48.300 --> 06:52.240
Dick's career abruptly ended after the publication of three novels very different from all the others,

06:52.480 --> 06:55.980
Vallas, The Divine Invasion, and The Transmigration of Timothy Archer.

06:56.280 --> 06:57.480
The last one is not science fiction.

06:57.480 --> 07:02.360
As Paul Williams told us in our last show, Dick wrote a number of mainstream novels which have yet to be published.

07:03.020 --> 07:07.360
Dick's science fiction novels and stories are generally plotted around the characters' perceptions of reality.

07:07.880 --> 07:13.260
We wondered if Dick were categorized as a science fiction writer simply because there was no other convenient pigeonhole in which to place him.

07:13.420 --> 07:14.280
Williams said no.

07:14.960 --> 07:25.780
Well, he was truly a science fiction writer, and I think that the primary meaning of that is that you belong to the club and you learn.

07:27.560 --> 07:32.700
By reading science fiction, he came up writing stories for all the science fiction magazines,

07:33.140 --> 07:41.380
and then he started writing novels for Don Wollheim at A's and was read only by science fiction readers,

07:42.300 --> 07:49.540
and was certainly aware of, as a pan, as a reader, all the science fiction, all the plotting devices,

07:49.540 --> 08:00.520
and the whole concept of the genre, the sense of those about to read science fiction.

08:02.000 --> 08:05.940
And I think that that's what it means to be a science fiction writer in a lot of ways,

08:06.040 --> 08:11.640
is to come up from that world and to stay within that world to whatever degree,

08:13.260 --> 08:15.500
at least with part of your work.

08:15.500 --> 08:17.400
And he definitely did that.

08:17.640 --> 08:23.580
He wasn't necessarily satisfied with that, not easy to understand.

08:25.280 --> 08:32.440
But he did, although he was not a great reader of it after adolescence or whatever,

08:33.260 --> 08:40.520
he really loved science fiction, and the people he wrote for and the people that he communicated with were pretty much in that world.

08:40.520 --> 08:50.640
At least, I think it diversified more in the last ten years, but still I would consider him very squarely a science fiction writer.

08:51.940 --> 08:54.200
Williams also told us how Dick felt about his own work.

08:54.820 --> 09:01.600
He always had a very self-deprecating or humble attitude towards his work,

09:01.600 --> 09:13.680
while at the same time always giving you to know somehow that he really took it as seriously and respected it as much as his most artful fans.

09:14.680 --> 09:18.200
What I'm saying is that he really knew how good it was.

09:20.940 --> 09:24.360
But he was able to be very humble about it.

09:37.980 --> 09:42.700
The apathetic response of publishers to Dick's experimental mainstream efforts bothered him.

09:43.380 --> 09:55.160
What frustrated him, and he was very frustrated by it, was primarily that he didn't have the freedom to write what he called experimental mainstream novels as well.

09:55.980 --> 10:03.220
And of course, it was a tremendous victory for him, finally, possibly, but he was aware of it before he died,

10:03.740 --> 10:14.320
when the Transmigration of Timothy Archer was published in hard cover to the first publisher that he submitted it to after writing the novel and so forth.

10:17.760 --> 10:19.500
Or actually, before writing the novel.

10:21.820 --> 10:26.960
So it was something that he always wanted to do, to write this kind of book.

10:27.860 --> 10:33.400
The ghettoization of him as a science fiction writer kept him from it for a long time.

10:34.540 --> 10:37.780
More with Paul Williams on his friend Philip T. Dick on our next show.

